The '''Rock Island Clean Line''' is a proposed 500-mile [[high voltage direct current]] (HVDC) [[Electric power transmission|transmission line]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.suntimes.com/business/11101405-420/deal-with-downstate-ill-cable-plant-to-bring-1450-jobs.html |title=Deal with Downstate cable plant to bring 1,450 jobs |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |date=2012-03-06 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826062938/http://www.suntimes.com/business/11101405-420/deal-with-downstate-ill-cable-plant-to-bring-1450-jobs.html |archivedate=2012-08-26 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=2016-01-29 }}</ref> The stated purpose of the line is to transport electrical power from wind energy dense states in the [[Midwestern United States]] ([[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]], [[South Dakota]] and [[Minnesota]]) to the energy markets in the [[Chicago, Illinois]], and cities further east. The planned line would run from the [[Sanborn, Iowa]] area to near [[Morris, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockislandcleanline.com/site/page/location |title=Maps & Location |publisher=Rock Island Clean Line |accessdate=2016-01-29 }}</ref> The developer, [[Clean Line Energy Partners]], is targeting an operational date of 2017.
The region where the line would start has large potential for wind generation, but currently already can produce all the electricity it can use or transport out of the region on existing transmission lines.<ref name="mwen">{{cite news |url=http://www.midwestenergynews.com/2011/12/05/new-transmission-line-would-ease-iowa-wind-power-bottleneck/ |title=New transmission line would ease Iowa wind bottleneck |last=Haugen |first=Dan |publisher=Midwest Energy News |date=2011-12-05 |accessdate=2016-01-29 }}</ref> The line would have the capacity to transport up to 3500 megawatts of power out of the region.<ref name="mwen" /> An economic study for the line estimates that it could transmit the power of eight 500&nbsp;MW wind farms in the [[siouxland]] area.<ref name=a1>{{cite report|last1=Carlson|first1=J. Lon|last2=Loomis|first2=David G.|last3=Solow|first3=John L.|title=Economic Impact Study of the Proposed Rock Island Clean Line|publisher=Loomis Consulting|url=http://www.rockislandcleanline.com/sites/rock_island/media/docs/RICL%20Economic%20Impact%20Study.pdf|date=2011-03-16|accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>
The Federal Electricity Regulatory Commission approved the line in May 2012. In November 2014, the Illinois Commerce Commission approved it. {{as of|January 2016}}, the Iowa Utilities Board has not yet approved it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockislandcleanline.com/site/page/regulatory-approvals |title=Regulatory Approvals |publisher=Rock Island Clean Line |accessdate=2016-01-29 }}</ref>
Opposition to the Rock Island Clean Line is organized by Block RICL, which claims that the line will carry mostly non-wind energy (i.e., coal) and will use an unreasonably large amount of land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blockricl.com/about-ricl |title=About RICL |publisher=Block RICL |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>
