The '''SS ''Wafra'' oil spill''' occurred on 27 February 1971, when SS ''Wafra'', an [[oil tanker]], ran aground while under tow near [[Cape Agulhas]], South Africa. Approximately 200,000 barrels of crude oil were leaked into the ocean.<ref>[http://www.incidentnews.gov/incident/6213 "Wafra"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017222011/http://incidentnews.gov/incident/6213 |date=17 October 2011 }}. Incident News. Retrieved 23 December 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.incidentnews.gov/entry/517267 "Cape Agulhas, South Africa: Incident Summary"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610115606/http://www.incidentnews.gov/entry/517267 |date=10 June 2012 }}. Incident News. 27 February 1971. Retrieved 23 December 2011.</ref> The larger part of the ship was refloated, towed out to sea, and then sunk by the [[South African Air Force]] to prevent further oil contamination of the coastline.
==Grounding and sinking== {{Location map+|Western Cape|caption=Western Cape, South Africa|width=250|relief=1|places= {{Location map~|Western Cape|lon_dir=E|lat_dir=S|lat_deg=35|lat_min=0|lat_sec=0|lon_deg=20.2|lon_min=0|lon_sec=0|label=Grounding|position=right}} {{Location map~|Western Cape|lon_dir=E|lat_dir=S|lat_deg=34|lat_min=50|lat_sec=0|lon_deg=20|lon_min=0|lon_sec=9|label=Cape&nbsp;Agulhas|position=top}} }} The ''Wafra'' left [[Ras Tanura]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] on 12 February 1971 bound for [[Cape Town]], South Africa, with a cargo of 472,513 barrels<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Federal supplement|volume= 477|author=United States Court of Claims|publisher=West Pub. Co.|year=1980}}</ref> (63,174 tonnes)<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=Zoologica Africana|volume= 6|title=The effect of oil pollution from the tanker "Wafra" on the marine fauna of the Cape Agulhas|author1=Day, John H. |author2=Cook, F. |author3=Zoutendyk, P. |author4=Simons, R |pages=209–219|url=http://www.mendeley.com/research/effect-oil-pollution-tanker-wafra-marine-fauna-cape-agulhas-4/|year=1971}}</ref> of Arabian crude oil on board.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=American Maritime Cases|volume= 3|publisher=Maritime Law Association of the United States|year=1980}}</ref><ref name="NOAA">{{Cite web|url=http://response.restoration.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/Oil_Spill_Case_Histories.pdf|title=Oil Spill Case Histories|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]|page=|location=Washington|date=29 May 1997}}</ref> Half the cargo was owned by [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron Oil Sales Co.]], and the other half by [[Texaco|Texaco Export, Inc.]]<ref name="USCA">{{cite court|url=http://ftp.resource.org/courts.gov/c/F2/573/573.F2d.717.77-7382.77-7358.308.438.html|litigants=Texaco Export, Inc., and Chevron Oil Sales Co. (Plaintiffs-Appellants) vs Overseas Tankship Corp. (Defendant) and Getty Tankers Ltd. (Defendant-Appellee) United Steamship Corp. (Defendant-Third-Party Plaintiff-Appellee) vs Getty Oil Co. (Third-Party Defendant-Appellant)|court=United States Court of Appeals, Second Circuit|date=2 March 1978|vol=Nos. 308, 438, Dockets 77-7358, 77-7382}}</ref>
The ship was rounding the southern tip of Africa at 6:30 am on 27 February 1971 when the piping that brought seawater on board to cool her [[steam turbine]] failed. The engine room flooded, incapacitating the ship. She was taken under tow the following day by the Russian steam tanker ''Gdynia'', which – finding the task too difficult – handed the tow over to the ''Pongola'' {{convert|7|mi|km}} off [[Cape Agulhas]], later the same day.<ref name="ctx"/> The tow cable subsequently broke, and the ''Wafra'' grounded on a reef near Cape Agulhas at 5:30 pm on 28 February. All six of the port cargo tanks, as well as two of the six center tanks, were ruptured, resulting in approximately 26,000 tons of oil leaking at the grounding site, of which 6,000 tonnes washed up at Cape Agulhas.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Pulse of the Planet: A State of the Earth Report from the Smithsonian Institution Center for Short-lived Phenomena|author1=Cornell, James |author2=Surowiecki, John |isbn=0-517-50065-5|publisher=Harmony Books|year=1968}}</ref> A {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} by {{convert|3|mi|km|adj=on}} oil spill resulted,<ref name="NOAA"/><ref name="Devanney"/> which affected a colony of 1200&nbsp;[[African penguin]]s on Dyer Island near [[Gansbaai]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a4sIbHJ8AVsC&pg=PA343|page=343|title=Marine Pollution: New Research|author=Hofer, Tobias N.|publisher=Nova Publishers|year=2008|isbn=9781604562422}}</ref>
The ship was refloated and pulled off the reef on 8 March by the German tug [[:de:Oceanic (Schiff, 1969)|''Oceanic'']], but started to break apart. To prevent further oil contamination of the coastline, the larger section was towed {{convert|200|mi|km}} out to sea to the edge of the continental shelf ({{coord|36|57|S|20|42|E|display=inline}}), leaving a {{convert|160|km|mi|adj=on}} oil slick in her wake. On 10 March 1971, [[Blackburn Buccaneer|Buccaneer]] aircraft of the [[South African Air Force]] attempted to sink her with [[AS-30L|AS-30]] missiles, but succeeded only in starting a fire. The ship burned for two days before a [[Avro Shackleton|Shackleton]] aircraft was eventually able to sink it with [[depth charge]]s in {{convert|1830|m|ft}} of water.
If the ''Wafra'' had been a twin screw, two engine room ship, loss of an engine would most likely not have caused the loss of the whole ship.<ref name="Devanney"/> At the time, the oil spill was in the top twenty most disastrous tanker spills on record.<ref name="Devanney">{{Cite book|url=http://www.c4tx.org/ctx/pub/tromedy2.pdf|title=The Tankship Tromedy: The Impending Disasters in Tankers|page=110|author=Devanney, Jack|location=Tavernier, Florida|year=2006|isbn=978-0-977-64790-3}}</ref>
==Aftermath== In the wake of the accident, the South African Department of Transport realised that despite many Very Large Crude Carriers (VLCCs) using the Cape sea route each year, the authorities did not have ocean-going tugs that were able to assist them in distress, and to protect sensitive marine areas by breaking up oil spills with chemical dispersants.<ref>{{cite book|year=1986|publisher=South Africa Dept of Information|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IOcwAQAAIAAJ|title=South African Digest}}</ref> They therefore set up an oil spill prevention service known as ''Kuswag'' (Coastwatch) and commissioned two new salvage tugs, the ''John Ross'' and ''Wolrade Woltemade''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ports.co.za/didyouknow/article_2004_04_26_0125.html|title=Historical Review of SA Oil Pollution Service|publisher=Ports and Ships|author=Hutson, Terry|date=31 January 2004}}</ref> The two tugs, with their {{convert|26200|hp|kW}} engines, held the record as the world's largest salvage tugs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Total Book of South African Records|author=Rosenthal, Eric|publisher=Delta Books|year=1982|isbn=0-908387-19-9|page=71}}</ref>
